its name is W these are V so that's what kind of&nbsp;
a physical pictorial definition of a vector but we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.660 --> 00:01:33.480
will want one that's a little bit more concrete so&nbsp;
that we can specify exactly what it is that we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:40.860
talking about one approach is to say that is an&nbsp;
n-tuple well for us n is 2 because we're working&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.860 --> 00:01:45.270
in two dimensions but you could also do this for&nbsp;
three or four dimensions so we just say that a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:45.270 --> 00:01:55.470
vector V is a ordered pair of numbers and we'll&nbsp;
see that that's also quite reasonable another idea&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.470 --> 00:02:01.110
is to connect it with physical quantities that&nbsp;
are naturally in vector form things like force&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:01.110 --> 00:02:08.490
velocity torque acceleration or even translation&nbsp;
these are all physical things that are naturally&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:08.490 --> 00:02:15.700
represented by vectors and another approach is&nbsp;
to say that well a vector is really just like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:15.700 --> 00:02:23.650
a point because if we have our coordinate plane&nbsp;
here like this then here's a point and to that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:23.650 --> 00:02:30.310
point we can think of associating the vector that&nbsp;
goes from the origin to that point so there's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.310 --> 00:02:36.790
natural identification between points and vectors&nbsp;
and sometimes very often these two notions are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:36.790 --> 00:02:46.090
confused it will be very important for us not&nbsp;
to confuse them points and vectors are separate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:46.090 --> 00:02:53.620
notions and that's a key insight into geometry&nbsp;
let's have a look at what actually we are going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.620 --> 00:03:02.200
to do we're gonna draw some inspiration from what&nbsp;
we did when we were doing arithmetic I remind you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:02.200 --> 00:03:09.070
that we started out discussing natural numbers 1&nbsp;
2 3 and at some point we wanted to introduce the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:09.070 --> 00:03:15.160
idea of an integer which in our minds included&nbsp;
not just the natural numbers 1 2 3 but also zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:22.570
minus 1 minus 2 minus 3 and so on now remind&nbsp;
you what we did what we did is we took pairs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:22.570 --> 00:03:30.190
of natural numbers m and n we wrote em less n&nbsp;
to represent the integer that we would usually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:30.190 --> 00:03:38.380
think of as M minus n we had a notion of equality&nbsp;
between these things so that M less n was equal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:38.380 --> 00:03:47.950
to K less L precisely when M plus L equals k&nbsp;
plus n so effectively what we did is we used&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:47.950 --> 00:03:55.870
the differences between natural numbers to define&nbsp;
what an integer was or to put it another way an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.870 --> 00:04:01.330
integer was really a pair of natural numbers where&nbsp;
it was the difference between those two natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:01.330 --> 00:04:07.300
numbers that encoded the integer so that's a&nbsp;
lot like what we're going to do with vectors&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:07.300 --> 00:04:18.640
here's our official definition of what a vector&nbsp;
is a vector is an ordered pair a B of points so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:25.870
it's a pair of points first one called a and&nbsp;
a second one called B and our notation for it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:26.530 --> 00:04:35.230
having a little arrow on top of the pair a B&nbsp;
now along with this definition you will won't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:35.230 --> 00:04:40.810
be surprised to hear that there's a notion of&nbsp;
equality we have to say when two vectors are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:40.810 --> 00:04:48.310
the same or equal so let's say that we have&nbsp;
points a 1 a 2 a 3 a 4 with all this with the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:48.310 --> 00:04:57.070
same kind of notation here that a 1 equals x 1 y&nbsp;
1 and a 2 equals x 2 y 2 and so on then we'll say&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.070 --> 00:05:07.270
that the vector a 1 a 2 equals the vector a 3 a 4&nbsp;
precisely when these two relations are satisfied&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:07.270 --> 00:05:16.390
when X 2 minus X 1 that's the difference between&nbsp;
the x coordinates of these two equals X 4 minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:16.390 --> 00:05:23.650
X 3 the difference between the x coordinates of&nbsp;
these two and when y 2 minus y 1 the difference&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:23.650 --> 00:05:31.840
between the Y coordinates here equals y 4 minus&nbsp;
y 3 the difference of the Y coordinates here in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:41.020
pictorial terms will say that this vector a 1 a&nbsp;
2 is equal to a 3 a 4 when the change in X from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:41.020 --> 00:05:48.190
X 2 to X 1 here is the same as the change in&nbsp;
X from here a 4 to a 3 and when the change in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:48.190 --> 00:05:53.980
Y from here to here is the same as a change in&nbsp;
Y from here to here that ensures that it's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:53.980 --> 00:06:02.350
relationship between these two points that defines&nbsp;
or captures the vector and I give us a new type&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:02.350 --> 00:06:10.150
of mathematical object which will denote by vector&nbsp;
that's a vector it's not a point it's not a number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:10.150 --> 00:06:16.990
it's not a circle it's a new type of mathematical&nbsp;
object let's have a look at an example or two so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.990 --> 00:06:25.630
here's our usual grid plane with x axis x y axis&nbsp;
here and I've got a point a 1 with coordinates&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.630 --> 00:06:34.630
1 1 and a point a 2 with coordinates 3 4 then&nbsp;
those two points determine a vector let's call&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:34.630 --> 00:06:43.370
it V written a1 a2 and physically we think vectors&nbsp;
being the directed line segment from a1 to a2 if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:43.370 --> 00:06:50.300
we wanted to write it out officially we'd write&nbsp;
a1 there a 2 there with a vector sign on top of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.300 --> 00:06:58.070
them now this is a cumbersome notation and our&nbsp;
notion of equality that we defined last time&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:58.070 --> 00:07:02.720
shows us that it's only the difference between&nbsp;
the x-coordinates and the difference in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:10.550
y-coordinates that really matters so we introduce&nbsp;
a new type of notation for this vector we record&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:10.550 --> 00:07:16.760
it by the difference in the x-coordinates the&nbsp;
final minus the initial x-coordinate and the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:16.760 --> 00:07:23.240
difference in the y-coordinates the final minus&nbsp;
initial y-coordinate and we put those two numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.240 --> 00:07:31.040
inside a round brackets that's different from&nbsp;
square brackets so square brackets represent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.040 --> 00:07:37.700
points round brackets now represent vectors&nbsp;
this is a very nice notation that keeps these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:37.700 --> 00:07:45.560
two ideas separate here's another example of the&nbsp;
same vector at the point a3 with coordinates for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:45.560 --> 00:07:58.610
to the point a 4 with coordinates 6 5 then a&nbsp;
vector associated to them is also 2 3 so again&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:58.610 --> 00:08:05.810
when we emphasize that vectors and points are a&nbsp;
different type of objects now at the University&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:05.810 --> 00:08:12.170
of New South Wales where I teach I often teach&nbsp;
linear algebra and unfortunately our students&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:12.170 --> 00:08:17.450
are often confused about the difference between a&nbsp;
point and a vector because we essentially use the&nbsp;&nbsp;

